  "prompt": "Why does Obama say ISIL instead of ISIS?",
  "response": "President Obama and some of his administration officials preferred to use the term ISIL (Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant) instead of ISIS (Islamic State of Iraq and Syria) for a few reasons:\n\n1. Geographic precision: The term \"Levant\" refers to a broader geographic region that includes Syria, Lebanon, Israel, Palestine, and parts of Jordan, which more accurately reflects the group's territorial ambitions.\n\n2. Avoiding religious terminology: Some argue that using \"ISIL\" instead of \"ISIS\" helps avoid giving the group legitimacy by not using the term \"Islamic State,\" which could imply the group represents Islam.\n\n3. Political and diplomatic considerations: The choice of terminology can be part of a broader diplomatic strategy to how the group is perceived and discussed.\n\nAfter Obama's presidency, many media outlets and government officials continued to use both terms somewhat interchangeably, with ISIS becoming more commonly used in general discourse.",
